Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from any of various places (in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Yorkshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, and elsewhere) called Woodhouse, or a topographic name for someone who lived at a ‘house in the wood’ (Middle English <i>wode</i>, <i>hous</i>, Old English <i>wudu</i>, <i>hūs</i>).","variant of   Woodiwiss  , from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, which by the 16th century was sometimes written as <i>wodowes</i>, <i>woodose</i>, and <i>wodehouse</i>. The confusion with <i>woodhouse</i> probably arose because both words (and both names) were pronounced /wudus/ or /wudǝs/ in local dialect.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Woodis","meanings":["English:","perhaps a nickname from Old English <i>wuduwāsa</i>‘faun, satyr’.","alternatively, a shortened form of   Woodhouse  ."]},{"name":"Woodiwiss","meanings":["English (mainly Derbyshire and Yorkshire): nickname from Middle English <i>wodewose</i>, <i>wodewese</i> (Old English <i>wudewāse</i>) ‘wild man of the woods’. This word was also used to denote a person dressed to represent such a being in a play or pageant. Wodewoses (male and female) were mythical creatures of English and ancient Germanic folklore, akin to the fauns and satyrs of Classical mythology. The surname may also have been acquired by someone who lived and worked in the woods or perhaps by an unusually hairy man."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":34,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma de Woodhouse was born about 1225, in Wentworth, Yorkshire, England, her father, William Woodhouse, was 24 and her mother, Mrs William Wodehouse, was 27. She married Robert Wentworth. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1266, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1225–about 1266":"umbes 1225–umbes 1266","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1244–1308":"1244–1308","1203–1238":"1203–1238","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","before 1225":"enne 1225","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1203":"1203","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1266":"1266","about 1225":"umbes 1225","about 1244":"umbes 1244","about 1266":"umbes 1266","1308":"1308","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1225–about 1266":"noin 1225–noin 1266","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1244–1308":"1244–1308","1203–1238":"1203–1238","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","before 1225":"ennen vuotta 1225","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1203":"1203","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1266":"1266","about 1225":"noin 1225","about 1244":"noin 1244","about 1266":"noin 1266","1308":"1308","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"ab